{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6d57fce1-b97f-4258-8bc1-3640e92db79b","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the easiest for .NET apps. Alternatively, use **PerfView** for deeper Windows-native ETW traces.\n\n### Quick approach: `dotnet-trace`\n\n```powershell\n# Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect CPU profile (stop with Ctrl+C or --duration)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Heavier approach: PerfView (ETW-based)\n\n```powershell\n# Download PerfView.exe from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\n# Run as admin:\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500 -CpuSampleMSec:1\n```\n\n### When to use which\n\n| Tool | Best for |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Quick managed-code CPU sampling, low overhead |\n| PerfView | Full system ETW traces, GC analysis, native + managed stacks |\n\n**Tip:** If you suspect a tight loop or thread contention, also grab a dump with `dotnet-dump collect -p <PID>` for thread analysis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a09f3aac-e104-4f82-96b9-768734059650","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question - no code changes or tool usage needed. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":395},"id":"e7e663ba-596b-4776-b432-cf5dc83dcdef","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:50:35.563Z","parentId":"fc1f3bd0-be54-4e18-a1a3-608d0533be4a"}
